\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
I try to teach towards disruptive innovation because of its powerful motivation
 in ambitious students.
 With that concept as the backbone of my philosophy, I employ three notable
 methods to achieve it.
 These methods are student development of a toolkit for the material, the
 concepts of immediate feedback, and three types of learning.
 I will now describe each of these three methods, followed by a short overview
 of teaching towards disruptive innovation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
During my graduate work, I took a time-intensive course in nuclear reactor
 kinetics.
 The material was difficult, and built upon itself.
 The material half-way into the class required the solution of concepts
 from a quarter way through the course to be solved before even beginning.
 The professor's suggestion was golden: he asked us why we hadn't created
 a tool to do the previous analyses.
 He showed us his repository of FORTRAN code, built over 30 years, that
 helped him quickly perform analyses that previously he had toiled over.
 I believe this concept is almost universally applicable, and more profound
 than he intended.
 Students internalize a concept better through creation of a tool, students
 will resent less the requirement to repeat analyses if they can use their
 tool, and each time they find an edge case that breaks their tool they
 will become reacquainted with the material while fixing it.
 This also draws the added benefit that students will generate skills through
 the creation of these tools (programmatic or otherwise) that will make
 them more desireable to employers, and more ambitious students may even
 make tools that can be used more broadly.
 I plan to integrate the creation of a toolkit by each student in every
 class I teach.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Immediate feedback, or at least proximate feedback, is a requirement for
 the nebulous 
\begin_inset Quotes sld
\end_inset

state of flow
\begin_inset Quotes srd
\end_inset

.
 Proximate feedback's importance is currently being touted by productivity
 authors and scientists alike 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Kotler2014,Csikszentmihalyi2000"

\end_inset

.
 All students have complained about the time required to recieve graded
 papers, programmers expended countless hours decreasing compile times,
 and industrial designers have even invented 3d printing partly as a way
 to prototype more quickly.
 It is clear that decreasing in time to feedback is important for students
 learning and enjoyment of learning.
 With current technological methods, there is no excuse for not having quick
 turnaround times.
 I believe that technology could be extended in classes past the level of
 multiple choice electronic quizzes: natural language processing can follow
 students problem solving strategies, visualization tools can compare student
 answers with test cases, and object oriented methodologies can allow students
 to place their solutions in a 
\begin_inset Quotes sld
\end_inset

black-box
\begin_inset Quotes srd
\end_inset

 and see how it solves a more integral problem.
 A setup integrating these concepts would be time-intesive to setup and
 to tune, but could have vast implications student assignments.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The final method crucial to my teaching methodology is more general.
 I am not alone in the belief that there are (at least) three types of learning.
 For me, material can be presented in three forms: descriptively, mathematically
, and visually.
 These are used organically in many instances already.
 Gaps in students' understanding occurs when one or more of these forms
 are absent.
 An interesting example of these three forms comes from nuclear engineering,
 and Karl Ott's description of the idea of neutron lethargy.
 Mathematically, the concept is straightforward; however, many are unable
 to understand lethargy until they read Ott's apt description of the idea
 through a golf description (that energy is distance from the pin, lethargy
 is distance from the tee box) and accompanying visualization 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Ott1989a"

\end_inset

.
 I strive to do this with all of my material.
 I am particularly interested in the use of visualization for teaching purposes,
 and besides graduate work in visualization, I have also created and maintained
 two visualization open source codes
