\begin_layout Standard
With the aforementioned three concepts, and other conventional teaching
 methods, I hope to develop classes that center around imbuing students
 with the desire to create disruptive innovations.
 The students will organically find that, to create those innovations, they
 require a deep understanding of the basic and advanced concepts that underlie
 the field.
 I believe another example may be best to describe this concept.
 Early in my schooling, I had a particularly engaging mathematics teacher,
 and it was clear why.
 Instead of starting a lecture with a title like 
\begin_inset Quotes sld
\end_inset

imaginary numbers
\begin_inset Quotes srd
\end_inset

, she started with a statement like 
\begin_inset Quotes sld
\end_inset

I'm going to teach you why cruise control works
\begin_inset Quotes srd
\end_inset

.
 A student will more likely cling on to 
\begin_inset Quotes sld
\end_inset

let's design a bridge
\begin_inset Quotes srd
\end_inset

 than 
\begin_inset Quotes sld
\end_inset

let's learn truss structures
\begin_inset Quotes srd
\end_inset

, and the same concept applies to 
\begin_inset Quotes sld
\end_inset

let's develop a better bridge than has ever been conceived
\begin_inset Quotes srd
\end_inset

 than 
\begin_inset Quotes sld
\end_inset

let's design a typical causeway
\begin_inset Quotes srd
\end_inset

.
 Paraphrasing from Nietzsche, a good why can motivate almost any how: a
 student will find almost any way to learn a concept if it is required for
 a passion project.
 It is with this overarching goal, and subfocus on the three methods involving
 creation of toolkits, use of proximate feedback, and three-pronged material
 descriptions, that I hope to teach students deeply and prepare them to
 become community, field, and even world changers.
\end_layout

